?CPrint|cmdPrint||Commands;Print;File Menu
?Tdialogs
The $BPrint$ command (under the $XFile|fileM$ menu) can print all or a 
portion of the layout.

When you select the $BPrint$ command, a grid is drawn on the layout which 
represents each printed page.  
Clicking on the layout will select (or unselect) pages to be printed.

?Gprint
The $BPrint$ dialog contains a number of control areas:
?HcmdPrintSize
The size of each page is controlled by:
?LSo
?LI
$BScale$ - up to 1:1.
?LI
$BWidth, Height$ - scaled size of each page.
?LI
$BMax$ - sets Width and Height to the maximum for the print $BScale$.
?LI
$BSnap Shot$ - adjusts the $BScale$, $BOrigin$ and $BAngle$ to produce a one-page snap shot of the layout.
?LI
$BFormat$ - Portrait or Landscape.
?LE

You can manually enter the $BWidth$ and $BHeight$ values to override the 
maximum values.  
You cannot enter values larger than the page size times the $BScale$.

The $BPrint Order$ option controls the printing order of the pages.
Relative to the Print Grid:
?LSo
?LI
$BNormal$ order is Columns first, Top to Bottom, Left to Right.
?LI
$BReverse$ order is Rows first, Left to Right, Bottom to Top.
?LE

Whether tracks are printed with one or two lines (representing the center line and rails) depends on the $BPrint Scale$.
If this value is smaller than or equal to twice the $XTwo Rail Scale|cmdPref$ on the $XDisplay|cmdDisplay$ dialog then tracks are drawn with two lines.
This corresponds to the way tracks are drawn on the main window,
adjusted to account for the greater resolution of most printers.
At 1:1 tracks are also drawn with a center line.

?? mswword
?P
??
The other options:
?LSo
?LI
$BEngineering Data$ - show title, user, date and other information in a box at the bottom of the printout.
?LI
$BIgnore Page Margins$ - use the physical page size.  
This allows the printouts to abut without trimming.
?LI
$BPrint Registration Marks$ - at 1:1 scale, print location markers every 3" (or 10cm).
This option is only enabled at 1:1.
This is useful for aligning multiple pages printed at different angles.
?LI
$BPrint Snap Grid$ - if the $XSnap Grid|cmdGrid$ is visible then it may be drawn on the printout.
This option is only enabled if the $BSnap Grid$ is visible.
?LI
$BPrint Rulers$ - print rulers on all edges of the page.
This option is only enabled if the $BAngle$ is $B0.000$.
?LI
$BPrint Roadbed Outline$ - lines representing the edge of the Roadbed.
The Roadbed will be printed if the $BWidth$ is greater than the track gauge.  Note: this option is most useful at 1:1.
This option is disabled if tracks would be drawn with only one line (instead of two).
?LE

?HcmdPrintOrient
The orientation of the print grid is controlled by:
?LSo
?LI
$BX$ - X co-ordinate.
?LI
$BY$ - Y co-ordinate.
?LI
$BAngle$ - of the grid.
?LE

You can set these values directly or by dragging on the layout.
$BShift-Left-Drag$ moves the grid and $BShift-Right-Drag$ rotates the grid.
The $BReset$ button resets the values to 0.

The $BPrint$ button prints the selected pages and removes the $BPrint$ dialog.  It is not enabled until you have selected some pages to print.

The $BSetup$ button invokes the 
$XPrinter Setup|printSetup|Help,Misc,Printer Setup$ dialog.

The $BClear$ button unselects all selected pages.

$BSuggested Uses:$

Use the $BSnapshot$ button to set the scale and orientation for a one-page printout of the layout.  Also set $BEngineering Data$ to add the Layout Title, Scale and other data for a summary.

Use $Xlayers|cmdLayer$ to control which tracks are visible (and printed).  Put benchwork, scenery or different tracks levels in separate layers and hide the layers you are not working with.

To transfer the drawing to the layout without printing at 1:1, make
the $XSnap Grid|cmdGrid$ visible and orient it to match your room or
layout table.
Check the $BPrint Snap Grid$ toggle and use the printed grid to transfer
measurements to your layout space.
You may want to change the $Xcolor|cmdRgbcolor$ of the $BSnap Grid$ to make it more visible on the printout.

When you print multiple pages you can check $BIgnore Page Margins$
so pages can be placed next to each other.
The tracks will line up
correctly without trimming or overlapping the pages. 
Note: there will be an unprintable margin around the edge of the page.

If you print at 1:1 for direct transfer to the sub-roadbed,
check $BPrint Roadbed Outline$ and set $BWidth$ to show lines for making cuts.

If you make printouts in strips at different angles at 1:1 (to follow tracks around a curve), check $BPrint Registration Marks$ to be able to align the separate strips.


