?CPrint to BitMap|cmdOutputbitmap||File Menu;Print,BitMap
?Tdialogs
This menu item creates a BitMap file of the layout.

?Gbitmap
The $BBitMap$ dialog specifies the style and size of the BitMap.  The three toggle
buttons ($BPrint Titles$, $BPrint Borders$ and $BPrint Centerline$) control whether the $XLayout Title|optionTitle$, the borders or Track Centerlines are printed on the BitMap.
The size of the BitMap is smaller if these are disabled.

Printing the Track Centerlines (also seen when zoomed in 1:1) is useful when you later print the BitMap full size for laying out track.

If the $XSnap Gird|cmdGrid$ is visible then it will be printed on the BitMap.

The $Bdpi$ (or $Bdpcm$ if using $XMetric units|perfUnits$) control specifies the 
number of pixels per inch (or centimeter) in the BitMap.
You can enter values from 0.1 to 100.
Larger values will result in a larger BitMap file.
BitMaps must be less than 32000 pixels in height or width.

The BitMap width, height and approximate file size is indicated.

Note: This command can create a very large file and consume a lot of memory and time.

Pressing the $BOk$ button invokes a $BFile Save$ dialog so you can choose the
file name for the BitMap.

The format of the file depends on the Operating System: on MS-Windows it is a Windows Bitmap (.BMP) file, on Linux it is a X11 Pixmap (.XPM) file.


