?CGrid Dialog|cmdGrid||Options Menu;Layout Parameters;Snap Grid;Grid
?Tdialogs

The $BGrid$ dialog, displayed by $BGrid$ on the $XOptions|optionM$ menu,
specifies the origin, angle and other parameters of the Snap Grid.
The Snap Grid controls the position of the cursor during the
$XCurve|cmdCurve$, $XCircle|cmdCircle$, $XModify|cmdModify$,
$XStraight|cmdStraight$, $XLine Drawing|cmdDraw$ and $XTurntable|cmdTurntable$ commands.

?Ggrid
The $BGrid$ dialog contains controls affecting the Horizontal and Vertical
Snap Grid lines.  Each dimension can be independently controlled.

?LSo
?LI
The $BSpacing$ value specifies the distance between Major Grid lines, which are drawn as solid lines on the layout.
?LI
The $BDivisions$ value adds the Minor Grid lines between the Major Grid lines, which are drawn as a series of dots on the layout.
You can specify 0 or 1 as a Division value which removes the Minor Grid lines.
?LI
The Grid can be enabled or disabled in each dimension via the $BEnable$ check box.
?LE
The origin and angle of the Grid can be adjusted directly or by dragging on the layout.
$BLeft-Drag$ moves the origin of the Grid, and $BRight-Drag$ rotates the grid.
$XShift-Right-Click|defRightClick$ displays a popup-menu allowing you to rotate the grid by various angles.

Whether the Snap Grid is drawn is controlled by the $BShow$ check box.
Also, if the layout is $XZoomed Out|editZoomOut$ the Minor and Major Grid lines may be too close together to be drawn.
The minimum pixel distance between Grid lines is controlled by the $BMin Grid Spacing$ value on the $XDisplay|cmdDisplay$ dialog.

$BNote:$ on slow machine drawing the Grid can take noticeable time.
You can control this by selecting a larger value for the $BMin Grid Spacing$.

?Gbgsnap
The $BGrid Buttons$ on the $XToolbar|toolbar$ can be used to Enable/Disable and to Show/Hide the Snap Grid.

