?BCircle Track|cmdCircle|bcircle|Commands;Curved Track;Flex-track;Creating Tracks
?Tcommands
A circle track is a special form of a curved track that extends 360 and has 
no End-Points.  
The three methods (with their accelerator keys) used to create a Circle Track are:

?LS
?LI
$Gbcircl1$ ($BControl-8$) Use the Fixed Radius specified on the $BCircle Radius$ control displayed on the $XStatus Bar|statusBar$.  Drag the Circle track into position.
?LI
$Gbcircl2$ ($BControl-9$) Drag from the edge of the Circle track to the Center.
?LI
$Gbcircl3$ ($BControl-0$) Drag from the Center of the Circle track to the edge.
?LE

The button to the left of the Circle track button selects which method will be invoked by the Toolbar button.

If the $XSnap Grid|cmdGrid$ is enabled then the Circle center will be constrained to the grid.

Circle tracks are useful for fitting curves into corners and other tight places.  
Also, they are good to establish initial layouts and finding out "what will fit".

You can join to and from circles, after which they become curved tracks.


?BHelix Track|cmdHelix|bhelix|Command;Curved Track;Flex-track;Creating Tracks;Helix
?Tcommands
A helix track is used to change the elevation of track in a restricted space.
A helix is drawn as a circle of track, but in 3 dimensions it would resemble a cork screw or the pattern of threads on a bolt.

?Gchelix
A helix is defined by the number of $BTurns$ and $BRadius$.

The helix dialog allows you to calculate these values based other parameters such as the $BElevation Difference$, $BGrade$ and $BVertical Separation$.
The $BAngular Separation$ is the difference in degrees between the tracks entering and exiting the helix.
Changing any of these values effects other values.
For example, increasing the $BRadius$ decreases the $BGrade$.
Changing the number of $BTurns$ affects the $BVertical Separation$ and either the $BRadius$ or $BGrade$.

In the case where different parameters could be affected
(for instance changing $BElevation Difference$ can affect $BRadius$ or $BGrade$)
the last parameter you changed will be preserved.
If you set the $BGrade$ and then $BElevation Difference$ then the $BRadius$ will be adjusted.

Changing $BVertical Separation$ affects $BTurns$ which must be an integer value (no fractions), and this in turn affects the $BVertical Separation$.
When you set $BVertical Separation$ you are specifying the minimum separation which is adjusted upwards to the actual value.

Note: only the $BRadius$ and $BTurns$ are used when creating the helix.
After joining the helix to other tracks, you will want to establish the heights of the End-Points at each end of the helix.
You can use the $XElevation|cmdElev$ command to do this.

A helix is placed the same way as a $XCircle Track|cmdCircle$ with the addition that you specify the number of turns as well the as the radius of the helix.  Then the helix is dragged into position on the layout.

You can join to a helix in the same way you join to a circle.  However, once joined the helix is still drawn as a circle of track.

A label for the helix is drawn at it's the center.
If the elevations are set (either by a Defined Elevation point or connecting to a Defined Elevation point) for the two ends of the helix then the label contains the computed grade and vertical separation between layers as well as the number of turns and total length.
The label can be moved or turned off by the $XMove Label|cmdMoveLabel$ command.


?BTurnouts and Sectional Track|cmdTurnout|bturnout|Commands;Turnouts;Sectional Track
?Tcommands
Turnouts (and sectional track) are created by the $BTurnout$ command.  
