?BHandlaid Turnouts|cmdHandLaidTurnout|bhndldto|Commands;Turnouts;Flex-track
?Tcommands

Handlaid turnouts are created by specifying 3 values:
?LSo
?LI
position of the $XFrog|defTurnoutFrog$
?LI
angle of the $BFrog$ (the frog number)
?LI
position of the $XPoints|defTurnoutPoints$
?LE

First select the position for the $XFrog|defTurnoutFrog$ on an existing track and then $BDrag$ away to specify the angle of the $BFrog$.
The angle in degrees and equivalent frog number is displayed on the status bar.
When you release, the line indicating the angle jumps to one side of the track to show you the center line of the new leg of the turnout.

Next $BClick$ and $BDrag$ to position the $XPoints|defTurnoutPoints$ for the turnout.  As you $BDrag$, tracks will be drawn showing the turnout.  When you release the turnout is created.

You cannot place the $BFrog$ or $BPoints$ on a turnout, circle or helix.  However, you can create overlapping Handlaid Turnouts.

There are constraints on where you can place the $BPoints$ in relation to the $BFrog$.
You cannot place the $BPoints$ too close the $BFrog$.
When placing Handlaid Turnout on a curved track you may get unexpected results, especially when placing the $BPoints$ a long way from the $BFrog$.
Try changing the $BFrog$ angle to get different results.

Note: the drawing is an approximation to show the location of the $BPoints$ and $BFrog$.
The piece of track considered (by $BXTrkCad$) to be a Handlaid Turnout is a short section of track located at the $BPoints$ and extending towards the $BFrogs$.
Other track segments are created between the $BPoints$ and $BFrog$ and a short straight segment is drawn after the $BFrog$.
These other segments are independent of the turnout and can be removed or modified, although this is probably not a good idea.


