?BModify Track|cmdModify|bmodify|Commands;Modify Track;Changing Tracks
?Tcommands
The $BModify$ command is used to change existing tracks and to extend them with new tracks.
This command works with an unconnected End-Point of a track.

Either the Left mouse button (for changing length or creating a tangent track) or
the Right mouse button (for extending with a new track) is used to select the
unconnected End-Point.

Any tracks that are created during the Modify command will have the following properties inherited from the first track: selected state, hidden state, scale, track gauge and Layer.

?cChanging Track Length:|||

$XLeft-Drag|leftdrag$ is used to change the length of a track segment,
 (or Table Edge, Benchwork, Dimension Line or Line).

$BLeft-Dragging$ the End-Point of a turnout (or other sectional track) causes a 
straight track to be created from the selected End-Point to the cursor.

You can change the length of a curve to form an almost complete circle if 
you drag the cursor almost to the other End-Point.  
Going past the other End-Point creates a very small curve.  
You cannot create a curve of greater than 360.

$BLeft-Dragging$ the End-Point of a $XTable Edge|cmdDraw$ allows you to move the End-Point to a new position.
If you move close to the End-Point of another Table Edge then the End-Point will be moved to it. 

?cCreating a Tangent to a Curve:|||

If you $BLeft-Drag$ beyond the radius of a 
$XCurved track|cmdCurve$ (but not a $XCircle|cmdCircle$)
a Tangent to the Curve will be created.

This will begin when the distance from the Curved track center to the cursor is
greater than 110% of the radius.
If you then move the cursor within the radius of the Curve then the $BChanging Track Length$
mode is in effect.

The Curve is shortened or lengthened as required.  

If $Xeasements|cmdEasement|Help,Misc,Easements$ are enabled then an easement curve 
will be generated (if required) to connect the old and new tracks.

?cChanging Track Radius:|||

$BShift-Left-Drag$ is used to change the Radius of $BStraight$ or $BCurved$ track segment.

Hold down the $BShift$ key and select the unconnected End-Point or a track.  The other End-Point must be connected to another track.  Now $BDrag$ the unconnected End-Point to change the Radius of the track.  Straight tracks can be made into Curved tracks and vice versa.

?cExtending a Track:|||

$XRight-Drag|rightdrag$ is used to 
extend a track with a straight or curved track.  
The selected End-Point determines the position and angle of the first 
End-Point of the new track.  
The cursor is dragged to set the second End-Point.
This is similar to creating a $Xcurved track|cmdCurve$.

A curved or straight track will be created, depending on the position of the 
second End-Point.

If $Xeasements|cmdEasement|Help,Misc,Easements$ are enabled then an easement curve 
will be generated (if required) to connect the old and new tracks.


?BJoin Tracks|cmdJoin|bjoin|Commands;Join Tracks;Easements;Spiral Transition Curves
?Tcommands
Any two tracks can be joined together.  
$BXTrkCad$ ensures that the connecting track is aligned properly.

?cJoining With New Track:|||

$BLeft-Click$ to select the first unconnected End-Point.  
A Red dot will be drawn to remind which track you selected.  
Then $BLeft-Drag$ to select the second unconnected End-Point and drag along the track to vary the radius 
of the connecting track.

$BXTrkCad$ moves the End-Points of the selected tracks as necessary to meet the connecting curve.  
In some cases the connecting track will be straight.  
If the selected End-Points are close to each other and aligned then the two 
are connected directly.

If enabled,
$XEasements|cmdEasement|Help,Misc,Easements$ 
will be automatically generated between 
tracks of differing radii.  
When using easements, there is a minimum radius as specified in the $BEasement$ dialog.  
You are not allowed to join tracks with less then this radius and the 
connecting track's radius must be greater than the minimum radius.

If there any errors while joining tracks (such moving beyond the end of a
track or using a curve with a radius smaller than the Easement radius),
then the joint track will be drawn in Red.
This serves as a visual cue that the connecting track can not be created.

Any tracks that are created during the Join command will have the following properties inherited from the first track: selected state, hidden state, scale, track gauge and Layer.

$XTurnouts and Sectional|cmdHotBar$ tracks can be joined to other tracks.  
$BXTrkCad$ extends the selected End-Point with a straight track to use in 
making the connection.  

You can join to a $XTurntable|cmdTurntable$, 
but the Turntable must be used as the second End-Point.

You also join to or from a $XCircle|cmdCircle$ which converts the Circle into a Curved track.

?cMoving To Join Tracks:|||

You can move $Xselected|cmdSelect$ tracks to join with another track.  All the selected
tracks are moved and rotated so the End-Points are aligned.

$BShift-Left-Click$ on two unconnected End-Points.  One must be $Bselected$ and the other
$Bunselected$.  The two End-Points will be joined by moving the $Bselected$ tracks.

See the Demos for examples of how to join tracks.


?BConnect Tracks|cmdConnect|bconnect|Commands;Connect Tracks
?Tcommands

This command is used with $BSectional Track$.

Occasionally pieces of
sectional track do not line up exactly, especially when creating figure-8's or passing sidings.  When laying out the actual track you can compensate for this by adjusting the individual tracks to provide a bit of slack.
This command simulates this process.

Click on each End-Point of the tracks you trying to connect.  Tracks will be moved slightly to overcome the gap.  If the gap is too large, the connection will fail, and you should try using other track pieces in your layout.

$BXTrkCad$ adjusts the positions of tracks connected to the tracks up to a track with more than two connections.  See the Demo for details.

If one (or both) the selected tracks is an Adjustable Section (such as Kato's Adjustable Track #20-050) then length of the track is changed to fill the gap.

You can undo the effect of the $BConnect$ command by $XSplitting|cmdSplitTrack$ the track to disconnect them and then use $BConnect$ command with $BShift-Left-Click$ on the unconnected End-Points to tighten the connections between the tracks. 


