?BSplit Track|cmdSplitTrack|bsplit|Commands;Modify Track;Splitting Tracks;Block Gaps
?Tcommands
The $BSplit$ command splits a track into two pieces at the selected point.  

If you select an End-Point of a track then the tracks are disconnected.
Otherwise, the track is split at the selected point, but the two tracks
remain connected.
To split and disconnect at a point, $Bsplit$ the track twice, (first splits and the second disconnects).

You cannot create a track shorter than the $XMinimum Track Length|cmdPref$.

This command is useful for placing tunnel portals or $XElevation Points|cmdElev$ at specific places.

Normally, you can not split a Turnout.  
If you hold the $BShift$ key then you can $BTrim$ a Turnout which replaces the portion of the Turnout between the split point and the End-Point with $Bflex-track$.
For Turnouts with more than one set of $XTurnout Points|defTurnoutPoints$, such as a Slip Switch or Scissors Crossover, you can not select a point between the $BPoints$.

$XShift-Right-Click|defRightClick$ displays a popup menu which can be used change the $Bblock gaps$ for the End-Point.  A block gap is drawn as a thick line at the End-Point.  Either or both rails can be gapped.

?BElevations|cmdElev|belev|Commands;Elevations;Modify Track
?Tcommands

The $BElevation$ command changes the Elevation of track End-Points.

?Gcelev

An End-Point can have one of several Elevation types:
?LSo
?LI
$BNone$ - no elevation defined.
?LI
$BDefined$ - a defined elevation at a specified height.
?LI
$BHidden$ - a defined elevation but not displayed on the layout.
?LI
$BComputed$ - height is based on height of closest neighbors.
?LI
$BGrade$ - grade is based on height of closest neighbors.
?LI
$BIgnored$ - End-Point is not considered in computations.
?LI
$BStation$ - assigns a name to the End-Point.
?LE

$BNote:$ Each End-Point can have only one of these attributes.
For example, an End-Point can not be a Defined Elevation and a Station at the same time.

In this command, $BDefined Elevation$ End-Points are indicated on the layout by Gold colored dots.
$BIgnored Elevation$ End-Points are indicated by Blue colored dots.

When an End-Point is selected on the layout by $BLeft-Click$, it is highlighted by a large Red dot and its Elevation type and values are displayed in the dialog.

$BShift-Left-Click$ splits the track at the specified point to add an Elevation point to the middle of a track.

The grade at the specified End-Point is displayed next to the $BGrade$ radio button.
For $BDefined Elevation$ End-Points, the grade on each side of the End-Point is displayed.

$BDefined Elevation$ End-Points are used to specify fixed heights of track End-Points.
Typically, this would be where grade changes or where clearances must be maintained.
Between $BDefined Elevation$ End-Points you can place $BComputed$ Elevations and $BGrade$ markers.
These values are not entered directly but are Computed Dynamically based on the $BDefined Elevations$ of connected tracks.
This allows you label elevations at intermediate End-Points without having the enter specific values.
You can also place $BComputed$ markers between a $BDefined Elevation$ point and the end of a track.

$BStations$ are used to provide information for the $XProfile|cmdProfile$ command.

All $BElevation$ (including $BGrade$ and $BStation$) labels are drawn on the layout outlined in boxes.  These may be moved by the $XMove Label|cmdMoveLabel$ command.  In addition, $BGrade$ labels have an arrow indicating the upwards direction.

?Gdchgelev

The $XTools|toolsM$ Menu contains commands to Remove or Raise/Lower the Elevations from selected tracks.  The entered value is added to all Defined Elevations on Selected tracks.  A negative value will lower the Elevations.

?? mswword
?P
??
?cComputing Dynamic Elevations|||

?Hcomputingelevations
Elevations of Tracks are computed in following steps.  
The colors listed in each step are used as the background color of the
Track Elevation Markers (if they are $Xenabled|optionLabelEnable$).
?LS1
?LI
The Shortest Paths between all $BDefined Elevations$ are computed.  
A Path stops at $BIgnored$ or $BDefined$ End-Points.
The Elevation of any Turnouts on these Paths with more than two connections 
are computed as the average Elevation inversely weighted by distance along the tracks to the
$BDefined Elevation$ points ($BBlue$).
?LI
The Elevation of any other tracks on the Shortest Paths are computed based on the distance along the tracks from the Turnouts computed in the first step and/or the $BDefined Elevation$ points ($BPurple$).
?LI
The Elevation of any remaining tracks is computed based on the average Elevation
of the tracks found in the first two steps that they
are (directly or indirectly) connected to,
inversely weighted by geometric distance ($BGold$).
?LI
Any remaining tracks are not connected to a $BDefined Elevation$ and do not have an Elevation.
?LE

The Elevation Computation is performed incrementally every time the layout is changed to keep all Elevations
in sync.
The performance of the computation is affected by the placement of the $BDefined Elevation$ End-Points and the number of Paths between them.
Place the $BDefined Elevations$ at points where tracks begin to branch (such as the throat of a yard or at the ends of a siding).
Also, use $BDefined Elevations$ to break the layout into areas so recomputation has fewer tracks and Paths to deal with.

?BProfile|cmdProfile|bprofile|Commands;Profile;Elevations;Modify Track
?Tcommands

The $BProfile$ dialog draws a profile showing Elevations, Distances and Grades for a $BPath$ on the layout.

?Gcprofile

Choose a $BPath$ by $BLeft-Clicking$ on End-Points.
As each End-Point is chosen, the Path is extended via the shortest route.
Selecting the end of the $BPath$ trims the $BPath$ back to a last $BDefined Elevation$ point (if any, otherwise the $BPath$ is cleared).

If no route is possible an error message is displayed.
There are several reasons why this might happen:
?LSo
?LI
The tracks are not connected.  Check this by $BShift-Left-Click$ing on one track using the $XSelect|cmdSelect$ command.
This selects all tracks connected (directly or indirectly).
See if the other track is selected.
?LI
One of the End-Points on the route is $XIgnored|cmdElev$.  Look for Blue dots on the expected $BPath$ when using the $BProfile$ or $XElevation|cmdElev$ commands.
?LI
The only route connects to a section of track that is already on the $BPath$ and is not the end of the $BPath$.
Remove the end of the $BPath$ until the connected track is not on the $BPath$.
?LE

The $BPath$ is drawn in the $XProfile Color|cmdRgbcolor$ (default Purple) on the Layout.

If the shortest $BPath$ is not what you want, you can choose End-Points that are closer to the end of the $BPath$.
Also, you can $XIgnore|cmdElev$ End-Points to prevent the $BPath$ from choosing a route through that End-Point.
$XShift-Right-Click|defRightClick$ displays a popup-menu that allows you to change the specified End-Point to be a $BDefined$, $BIgnored$ or $BNone$ Elevation End-Point.

Each $BDefined Elevation$ End-Point on the $BPath$ is drawn as a Vertical bar, labeled with its height and distance from the beginning of the $BPath$.

The $BGrade$ between points is displayed between the Vertical bars.
The $BGrade$ line is drawn in Blue if that portion of the $BPath$ does not contain more than one Shortest Path between Defined Elevation End-Points.
Otherwise it is drawn in Red, to indicate the grade is an average and the actual grade may vary for any particular track segment.
See $XComputing Dynamic Elevation|computingelevations$ for more details.

$BStations$ on the $BPath$ are displayed along the bottom of the $BProfile$.

You can change the heights of $BDefined Elevations$ by $BLeft-Dragging$ on the Profile Window.
As you $BDrag$, the new Elevation and Grades to each side are displayed at the bottom of the Profile dialog.

The $BDone$ button closes the dialog.

The $BClear$ button removes all points from the $BPath$.

The $BPrint$ button prints the dialog.  The aspect ratio is preserved on the print-out.
You will probably want to print in Landscape format.


